# TallyBadger development rules

## Git and delivery

- Build **features and bug fixes on a branch**; do not land substantive work by committing straight to the default branch (`main`/`master`).
- If currently on the default branch (`main` or `master`), create and switch to a feature/bugfix branch **before making any code changes or commits**.
- Merge to the default branch (`main`/`master`) only through a **pull request** (self-review is OK; the PR is the audit trail and review surface).
- Use **squash merge** (or equivalent) when merging PRs so the default branch (`main`/`master`) stays a linear, readable history unless the team explicitly chooses otherwise.
- **Link work to GitHub issues:** in the PR description, reference issues with keywords GitHub understands, e.g. `Fixes #42`, `Closes #42`, or `Refs #42` (see [GitHub linking](https://docs.github.com/en/issues/tracking-your-work-with-issues/linking-a-pull-request-to-an-issue)). Put the primary link in the **PR body** so it survives squash; repeat in commit messages if you like, but the PR body is the reliable place.
- Updates to data model need to be reflected in the export-dev-seed make target.

## Testing (ship tests with the change)

- Every **feature** or **bug fix** includes **at least one new automated test**; add more whenever needed to cover behavior and prevent regressions.
- **Backend** (`src/tallybadger/`, `tests/`): extend **pytest** for API and domain logic (e.g. FastAPI `TestClient`, unit tests). Add **integration tests** when behavior depends on PostgreSQL or migrations.
- **Frontend** (`frontend/`): once the UI stack is chosen, **every frontend change** must include **automated tests** (e.g. component tests plus e2e or smoke UI tests—match the stack). Until non-trivial UI exists, focus tests on the API; as soon as UI code ships, UI tests are **mandatory** for those paths.
- **Design for testability:** keep domain and ledger rules **testable without HTTP** where practical; inject config/DB/session dependencies; avoid hidden globals and side effects that block assertions.

## Engineering defaults

- **Money:** use `Decimal` or integer **minor units**—never `float` for currency in new code.
- **API contract:** treat published routes and stable JSON shapes as contracts; update tests and docs when they change.
- **Secrets:** never commit credentials; use env (e.g. `TALLYBADGER_*`) or secret stores.
- **Database:** ship SQL migrations in `sql/` (or the chosen migration tool) with the same PR as code that depends on them; prefer reversible or additive steps when data is live.

## PR hygiene

- PR description states **what changed**, **why**, how to **verify** (commands run, screenshots for UI when relevant), and **which issue(s)** it addresses (`Fixes #…` / `Refs #…`).
- **Tracking:** features and bugs live in **GitHub Issues**; implementation PRs should reference those issues so history stays traceable.
